<content>
<section id="fs-id1167661260908" class="learning-objectives">
<title>Learning Objectives</title><para id="fs-id11713605736962">By the end of this section, you will be able to:</para>
<list id="fs-id1167663929131">
<item>Compare direct and indirect agglutination</item>
<item>Identify various uses of hemagglutination in the diagnosis of disease</item>
<item>Explain how blood types are determined</item>
<item>Explain the steps used to cross-match blood to be used in a transfusion</item>
</list>
</section>
<para id="fs-id1167663639521">In addition to causing precipitation of soluble molecules and flocculation of molecules in suspension, antibodies can also clump together cells or particles (e.g., antigen-coated latex beads) in a process called <term>agglutination</term> (<link target-id="OSC_Microbio_18_04_agg" document="m58884"/>). Agglutination can be used as an indicator of the presence of antibodies against bacteria or red blood cells. Agglutination assays are usually quick and easy to perform on a glass slide or <term>microtiter plate</term> (<link target-id="OSC_Microbio_20_03_Microt"/>). Microtiter plates have an array of wells to hold small volumes of reagents and to observe reactions (e.g., agglutination) either visually or using a specially designed spectrophotometer. The wells come in many different sizes for assays involving different volumes of reagents.</para>
<figure id="OSC_Microbio_20_03_Microt">
<media id="fs-id1167663622789" alt="A plastic plate about the size of a hand with wells in a grid. The top is labeled 1-12 and the side is labeled A-H.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OSC_Microbio_20_03_Microt.jpg"/>
</media>
